<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911211-0145</DOCNO><DOCID>911211-0145.</DOCID><HL>   Santa Fe Energy   Agrees to Acquire   Adobe Resources   ----   By Robert Johnson   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>12/11/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4</SO><CO>   ADB SFR</CO><MS>ENERGY (ENE)</MS><IN>OIL-SECONDARY (OIS)PETROLEUM (PET)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>PETROLEUM MARKET (PET)ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)TEXAS (TX)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   HOUSTON -- Santa Fe Energy Resources Inc., hoping for along-term recovery in natural-gas prices, agreed to acquireAdobe Resources Corp. in a stock swap valued at about $500million.   Santa Fe, an oil and gas exploration concern whose currentreserves are 90% oil, said the acquisition will add naturalgas assets in the Gulf of Mexico to its existing reserves andprovide &quot;higher immediate revenues.&quot;</LP><TEXT>   But additional short-term net income from Adobe, a NewYork-based oil and gas exploration company, is unlikely. Forthe first nine months, Adobe posted a loss of $5.8 million,or 66 cents a share, on revenue of $126.1 million. The redink reflected a summer when natural gas prices fell tofive-year lows.   Santa Fe said the definitive agreement will swap 0.6196share of its common stock for each share of Adobe common.Adobe has about 30.7 million common shares outstanding, andSanta Fe has about 63.8 million.   The transaction is the latest and among the largest in aseries of buy-outs of natural gas companies this year.Natural gas companies are widely considered bargains on WallStreet because of depressed prices. Many have been dismissingemployees, closing wells and selling off assets.   In late New York Stock Exchange trading yesterday, SantaFe's common shares were quoted at $9.50, down 12.5 cents.Adobe's common shares were quoted at $6.25, up 12.5 cents inlate trading on the Big Board.   Terms of the transaction also call for each of Adobe's 4.2million 9.2% convertible preferred shares to be swapped atthe rate of one for each 0.5974 share of Santa Fe commonstock plus 0.5065 share of a new convertible series of SantaFe preferred stock.   In addition, each of Adobe's 4.9 million 12% preferredshares are to be converted into 0.7029 share of Santa Fecommon stock plus 0.5959 share of the acquiring company's newpreferred series.   The transaction is subject to approval by stockholders ofboth companies.</TEXT></DOC>